  "description": "The Amesha Spentas (also spelled Amesha Spentas, Avestan: Aməša Spəṇta) are a group of divine entities in Zoroastrianism, emanating from Ahura Mazda, the supreme creator god. Their name translates to \"Bounteous Immortals\" or \"Holy Immortals.\" They represent different aspects and virtues of Ahura Mazda and serve as intermediaries between him and humanity. They are not simply abstract concepts but are considered distinct beings, each with a specific role in maintaining cosmic order and guiding humanity towards righteousness. Zoroastrian cosmology posits that the Amesha Spentas were created by Ahura Mazda to help him combat Angra Mainyu (Ahriman), the force of evil and chaos. Each Amesha Spenta is associated with a specific aspect of creation, such as the earth, water, plants, animals, fire, and humanity. They are also linked to specific virtues, such as truth, righteousness, devotion, perfection, and immortality. The Amesha Spentas are venerated in Zoroastrian prayers and rituals, and their qualities are emulated by Zoroastrians in their daily lives. They represent the ideal state of existence and serve as a model for human conduct. The concept of the Amesha Spentas highlights the Zoroastrian emphasis on ethical monotheism and the importance of striving for spiritual perfection.",
  "symbols": [
    "persian symbolism"
  ],
